Reasoning: The paper deals with the problem of computing the minimal number of resources necessary to fully exploit the concurrency of a given workflow, which involves analyzing the computational complexity of two versions of the problem. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the sub-categories of computer science that deal with algorithms, data structures, software engineering, programming languages, and computational complexity. Specifically, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.SE (Software Engineering) are likely because the paper proposes an algorithm to approximate the concurrency threshold of free-choice Petri nets. cs.PL (Programming Languages) is also likely because the paper deals with the core of business processing languages such as BPMN or UML Activity Diagrams. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) and cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) are less likely but still possible because the paper analyzes the computational complexity of the problem.
